    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        The volume of a sphere is given by:
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Volume}= \frac{4}{3} \pi r^3</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        where <m>r</m> is the radius of the sphere.
    </p>


    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the volume of the figure below: (Use <m>\pi = \frac{22}{7}</m>)
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="volume-of-a-sphere-1 ">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the sphere
                    \shade[ball color=blue!30!white, opacity=0.8,very thick] (0,0) circle (3cm);

                    % Draw the radius line
                    \draw[red, very thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,0) -- (3cm,0) node[midway, above] {28 cm};

                    % Draw the center point
                    \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt);



                    % Draw a dashed line to show the hidden part of radius
                    \draw[red, dashed] (0,0) -- (-3cm,0);

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The radius of the sphere is given as <m>28 \text{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The volume is given by:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume} =\amp \frac{4}{3} \pi r^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{4}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times (28)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{4 \times 22 \times 28^3}{3 \times 7} \text{ cm}^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp  10922.67 \text{ cm}^3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The volume of the sphere is <m>{\color{blue}10922.67 \text{ cm}^3}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Moraa made a spherical cake balls of diameter <m>4.2 \text{ cm}</m>. If she had a minced cake of 
                <m>194.05\, \text{cm}^3</m>, find the number of cake balls she made from the minced cake.
            </p>

        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Find the radius of one cake ball:
            </p>
            <p>
                The radius is half of the diameter:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>r = \frac{4.2}{2} = 2.1 \text{ cm}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find the volume of one cake ball
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume }= \amp \frac{4}{3} \pi r^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{4}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times (2.1)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{4 \times 22 \times 2.1^3}{3 \times 7} \text{ cm}^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp  38.808 \,\text{ cm}^3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find the number of cake balls
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{Number of balls}= \amp \frac{\text{Total volume}}{\text{Volume of one ball}} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{194.05}{38.808} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 5 \, \text{ balls}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, Moraa made <m>{\color{blue}5 \, \text{ balls}}</m>  cake balls from the minced cake.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The figure below shows a globe with a radius of <m>35 \text{ m}</m>. 
                Find its volume.(Use <m>\pi=3.142</m>)
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="volume-of-a-sphere-2">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the sphere
                    \shade[ball color=blue!70,very thick] (0,0) circle (2cm);
                    
                    % Draw equator line
                    \draw[dashed,very thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2cm and 0.5cm);
                    \draw (-2,0) arc (180:0:2cm and 0.5cm);
                    
                    % Draw vertical meridian
                    \draw[dashed,very thick] (0,-2) arc (-90:90:0.5cm and 2cm);
                    \draw (0,2) arc (90:270:0.5cm and 2cm);
                    
                    % Draw radius
                    \draw[thick, yellow] (0,0) -- (0,2) node[midway, right] {$28$ m};
    
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The radius of the globe is given as <m>28 \text{ m}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The volume is given by:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume} =\amp \frac{4}{3} \pi r^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{4}{3} \times 3.142 \times (28)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{4 \times 3.142 \times 28^3}{3} \text{ m}^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp  91964.24533 \text{ m}^3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The volume of the globe is <m>{\color{blue} 91964.25 \text{ m}^3}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
